The first virtual service provider will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The Czech mobile market is relatively advanced and our service providers offer virtually the same services as their Western European partners.
However, we are missing something here - a virtual provider that forces classic service providers to reduce prices.
Maybe it won't be for long.
On Mobil.cz, we have often said that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
Furthermore, this was confirmed by ČTU, which pointed out that the text was more expensive in the Czech Republic than in the rest of the Union.
After the last step by the European Commission, the regulation of roaming charges may therefore result in a contradictory situation - texts sent abroad to some Czech mobile operators will be cheaper than those of the home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking the competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, because we have three mobile networks and our penetration is above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed by Pavel Dvořák, President of the Council of the Czech Telekom Office, who said a few times earlier that there is no place for another service provider in the Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic service provider with its own network probably does not have much chance (however, it would probably be difficult to find frequencies).
But there is another option - the virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that brought significant price reductions, and then the classical service providers had to react.
In the meantime, even before the entry into the market of large fish such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in Great Britain, there were voices similar to ours.
However, it has been shown that such service providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, for example, we don't have to go too far.
This February we informed you about Mobilking's virtual service provider's departure in Poland.
This service provider has managed to obtain more than 100 000 customers and become the fifth largest service provider there in less than six months.
Meanwhile, Mobilking is behind the Penta financial group, which is the owner of the U: line in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the possibility of focusing on a much smaller target group.
In order to operate effectively, you need a lot less customers than the traditional service provider.
It does not involve relatively high costs of construction, mobile network operation and maintenance.
Virtual service providers in the world usually show up as low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which are often compensated by fewer services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers texts that are at least 50% cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move to bet on a target group.
This service provider is specifically focused on men.
"Real men choose the Mobilking Service - who they like, who they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of this virtual service provider, Mobile Entertainment Company.
It's hard to tell if a vision like Poland can work for us.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesperson for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach, which is based on the majority of virtual service providers.
In addition, it is relatively satisfied from the point of view of the supply of services. '
There is no chance in the Czech Republic, claimed by mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but conciliation in the Czech Republic does not seem to be very hopeful.
Mobilking will be launched in other countries in our region, "said Jana Studničkova, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, in his interview with Mobil.cz.
It has indirectly demonstrated that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not very sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competition can be established.
For some time now, the GTS Novera group has stopped hiding its interest in the launch of the virtual service provider, which is to take another step in order to make Telesica O2 a real competitor in the company's customer field.
"We are very interested in providing our customers not only wired but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
This possibility has been renegotiated with all Czech mobile operators.
Some of them have already made progress in the negotiations, "says Pavel Kaidl, spokesperson for the group.
Maybe now's a better time.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual service provider could be lucky by the end of the year.
But for the time being, his birth is surrounded by a wall of impenetrable silence.
"At this moment, we do not believe that a full-fledged virtual service provider should be placed on the Czech market.
Unlike other markets, the Czech market is very special.
So far, we have not been invited by an unequal subject offering a complex and serious project in this area, "he mentioned to Mobil.cz about the press department of Vlastimil Sršeă, Telefónica 02.
The specific situation of the Czech market is also referred to by the other operators.
Martina Kemrová, the spokesperson for T-Mobile, with the exception of O2, adds: "We have not yet recorded any viable and double-sided business projects that could be further funded."
And he added: "In the T-Mobile network by the end of the year, it is unlikely that any virtual service provider will show up.
At this point, we should have a specific agreement on our table to think about in the short term. "
Vodafone will focus its attention on meeting its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual service providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
This is what we consider to be the most rewarding in terms of clients.
The main strategy of Vodafone is to find partners in this area to build networks shared with fast mobile Internet. '
Responsible offices - on a string with service providers
The procedure of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another service provider would mean an increase in competition, a decrease in prices and a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competition to enter?
When the service providers have something important, they are able to cooperate, they are also testifying to the string around the birth of the U: line.
The biggest pressure on ČTU was probably around the birth of the T-Mobile company's U: thread.
The publicly available information from the ČTU website shows this.
But right now, the U: phone is a good argument as to why we should not allow the entry of the virtual service provider.
Martina Kemrová added: "The environment of the competition in the mobile market has recently been affected by the access of the fourth mobile operator to the market.
In view of the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player to the market and its services would impose high requirements. '
In view of this attitude of mobile operators, however, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory bodies is absolutely astonishing.
In the meantime, it is not only the attitude of ČTU, which unfortunately has no right to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
Only the Economic Competition Office is entitled to do so.
However, the office is typical of the whole problem.
"The entry of a virtual service provider into a mobile market would be possible only after the contract between a mobile service provider and a virtual service provider is concluded to lease the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, since the offer of potential interested parties was unlikely to be of interest to traditional operators, "he said, answering our question, Kristián Chlapua, of the External Relations Department of the Economic Competition Office.
A statement made in this way would probably not surprise anyone from the representatives of the service providers.
However, from the office that should represent the interests of consumers and also make sure that no one can abuse their position on the market, this is more than strange.
In particular, if Kristian Chalupa adds: "Foreign countries, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephony services'.
However, it is likely that the interests of UOHS do not include pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the price reduction.
In this case, it is indeed shocking to see a very touching harmony from the reaction of the three mobile operators.
The question whether it is a coincidence is almost self-evident.
As with the filling stations, the exact same gas prices are probably just the work of chance and tough competition.
"The Office did not discover any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a leading position, i.e. a more proportionate responsibility for their market activities.
The means necessary to open the mobile market for virtual service providers are likely to be missing for the telecommunications regulator, "said Chalupa.
The presentation of the leading position on the market is one of many points of dispute.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČÖG, on the basis of which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, no Czech operator is in a leading position in such a market.
However, some legal experts also offer a different approach - the approval of the network operator is always required for the creation of a virtual service provider.
And the mobile provider, relatively logically, has a monopoly on its own network.
So it's necessarily dominant in a particular segment.
However, even if we did not accept this argument, it should be a minimum warning for UOHS that three mobile operators are acting remarkably in the same way.
In the meantime, complaints from interested parties (including GTS Novera, which has already been mentioned) show that they face very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTU is a relatively common trick in telecommunications with which UOHS takes its hands off the entire case.
We've seen this before in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act, the extension of the powers of ČTU in the field of economic competition could not be carried through in telecommunications, although many experts were hoping to improve the situation.
The representatives of UOHS need to know this well, but they probably have different interests.
It works when no one's watching.
Meanwhile, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual service providers, many of which already operate in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies issuing their own mobile telephone service price lists, which are, however, only partially public.
We're talking about multi-annual marketing companies.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies usually only go to the selected ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic company client against the provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a senior customer, you will then receive special offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-recruitment.
"If there were cases of which you are talking, there could be a breach of contract conditions which we would be dealing with and which could lead to the completion of cooperation with that company," he answered our question about this problem to Martina Kemrova.
However, it is highly unlikely that news of this kind of activity would not have reached the responsible people of mobile operators.
In particular, there may be thousands of customers in the case of the three companies mentioned.
In the meantime, no provider will defend against such a procedure.
They do not have negligible profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not pose a particular threat to their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows similar speculation, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card is not listed in their names in their phones, so they cannot fully have it as the general customers of mobile operators. '
But that's exactly what the CBI should be weird about.
In addition, another question arises for UOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to similar procedures, why are they blocking the birth of the virtual service provider?
It should be added that UOHS has a relatively strong power to uncover such an activity, and if it does not want to do so, it does not need to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they have not suspected anything of doing so and that their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we're not the most expensive
As has already been said a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market has resulted in a noticeable price reduction in services.
In the meantime, in virtually all countries where virtual service providers were created, classical service providers have tried to prevent them from being created more or less.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, possibly too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services etc.
In the developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened at this very moment, which in no way protected the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Then, even with formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are giving each other the whole case.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that indefinite competencies are good for them in these cases.
But let's not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider is really coming to us soon, the Czech mobile market may be on the move again.
If a provider would allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, it is difficult for UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of further interested parties.
And we may not be making more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
