Rats have feelings, too.
A rat or a moth is on the run in the event of danger.
The neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that animals have feelings.
But how can you examine whether they feel the same way when they behave like us?
The Internet journal "Edge" has been published by famous scientists for years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE is looking at the answers to the question "What do you think is real without being able to prove it?" in one of its series.
I believe that animals have feelings and other state of mind without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as we examine other species and investigate the issues of perception or consciousness in general, we arrive in difficult terrain, as hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals, pretending to be dead, running or attacking.
People behave in a similar way, from which some researchers conclude comparable subjective experiences.
But I don't believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experiences to animals.
On the one hand, human consciousness-related circuits almost always contain the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and implementation / management functions).
This wide area is higher in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely lacking in other organisms.
At least in the aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as the consciousness of who we are, or, in the case of planning and decision-making ability, it can be reasonably assumed that man is different from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the language nature of man: Since a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals may be excluded.
However, even if it were not dependent on the language, the language would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is probably very different from most of our consciousness states.
It is therefore difficult to determine what consciousness can be like for other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and because of the special hardware, it cannot be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my interpretations relate to the content of conscious living, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is likely to be more accessible to science.
The consciousness processes of animals, regardless of their content, could be examined, and this is precisely what happens in the case of experiments on short-term memory of primates, especially in the case of visualisation.
However, in this assumption also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the neural connections of consciousness than on the causality mechanisms: both can be the same or not.
Interestingly, this hypothesis also emphasises the importance of prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualisation.
What does that mean about emotions?
I'm leading this back to the fact that an emotional system, like fear, is activated in the brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we are when the activity of the protection system located in the brain (or its consequences such as physical reactions) occupies a working theory.
Thus, emotions are closely linked to those areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of primates and especially humans.
In addition to language, the perception is divided into subtle stages, because, with the help of words and grammar, we are able to distinguish and categorise conditions so that we describe them to others.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio is of the opinion that emotions are derived from simpler activities in the body perception areas of the cortex and the brain stem, as is Jaak Pankseep, who, however, is more focused on the brain stem.
As this network has not changed very much in human evolution, it can easily play a role in global emotions of species.
In purely hypothetical terms, I can't deny that, but I find it unjustifiable.
Pankseep believes that what seems to be fear in rats and humans in both cases probably feels like how to check whether rats and humans feel the same way when they behave in the same way.
A cockroach on the run in the event of danger, does he feel fear?
In my opinion, only similar behavior is not yet evidence of the same experience.
Although neural comparisons continue to help, rats and humans have similar brain strains, but cockroaches don't have brains.
But the brain stem is responsible for the emotions?
And even if it could be proven in terms of humans, how can we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, but maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have feelings.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And since their emotions are supposed to be fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I am more interested in the emotional behaviour of rats than in emotional emotions.
In any case, there is progress in this area at the neural level if we measure the same in rats and humans.
Just like in rats, I don't search for language or consciousness, I don't search for emotions, because I don't know if they exist.
