In the experience park in Greater Orlando, a few miles away from everything that shines, loud and powerful, there is a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience were born.
Eatonville, the first pure black city that was integrated into the country and which was Zora Neale Hurston's childhood home, is no longer as simple as he described in 1935: "the five lakes, three croquet tracks, 300 brown leather, 300 good swimmers, lots of guava and two schools without prison."
It's a pilgrimage now.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee attended the annual Zora Festival in honor of the most famous female writer of Harlem Renaissance, Hurston.
Yet, in many ways, the city described and made a tourist attraction, which is also in the Florida travel book of the Federal Writers' Project of the Crisis Age, is distinct from its surroundings.
It's just as independent, dignified and shut-down as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that the black people in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white people who "know so little about us that they don't know what they're missing."
Even in the year when the black presidential candidate, Barack Obama, encourages open discussion on the racial issue, many of us here are distrust of outsiders' glances.
"We care very much about how to tell our story," said the 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who lived here all his life and was a member of the oldest church in the city.
"You have to say it correctly."
Eatonville has long been characterised by a paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historic model of the black show, but it is a community of almost 2400 people, where poverty indicators can double the national average.
Partly a literary node, and partly an example of a culture of American slavery, sometimes looked down, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black, which flourishes in the shade of oak trees.
It is not surprising, therefore, that the residents here are both proud and defensive.
The picture of Eatonville has been important since Zora (everyone here calls Hurston).
In the books written in the honest, strong dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes were Watching God" (1937), he introduced his hometown to the world.
The five paragraphs of the Florida guidebook have transformed the city, which lies next to Route 17. This road leads from the long forgotten headquarters of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was both brave in life and in literature, like the drum roll, introduced his readers into the business of the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then looked into the more intimate spheres.
He wrote: "To the right of the road we can find modern public school with a brown edge, with carefully organized yards and playgrounds, which Howard Miller provides, although he can barely read and write."
He mentioned the widow Dash's new husband, and he wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of drinks and anything that might be needed in temporary accommodation."
So in a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to autonomy, but also illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
Clearly, the Fodor's guidebook presented it differently.
This description really didn't suit everyone.
"Zora said things the way they were," said the 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls. Hurston made them immortal by quoting the deaf songs that men sang about their beauty.
He added, "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as the living freak who used to visit home after his family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
The 77-year-old Augustus Franklin recalled that when Hurston stormed into the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a beating Chevrolet, smoking cigarettes, and in long trousers in a city where even today people are proud of their dignified attire.
Most people were enchanted, said Franklin, but a lot of people were.
"People were always happy to see Zora," said Franklin.
However, on the terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, swinging in his chair, "He never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor, and his books were no longer published.
It seemed that along with most of the world, Eatonville had forgotten about it.
Although he was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, he was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where he used to live.
There were no significant commemorations in Eatonville or large public readings.
"I don't think they understand how much he has enriched the world or what he has left us at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of the book "The Hurston biography," published in 2003, wrapped in the Rainbow. "
