Retrieval DUIs will be obliged to install "Alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior would, after violating three drunk driving rules, require the driver to install a device that would prevent the vehicle from being started if the driver was in a state of drinking or not blowing into the structure.
The proposal was presented in June and is now being dealt with by the Office of the State's Attorney's Office, according to which the pilot project will last for a year.
Since the aim of the project is to restore it to the market, the driver will also have to take part in a repeat course on transport education.
In addition to the Agency for Transport Safety, the pilot project includes the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Institute of Automotive Technology (FITSA).
According to the statistics, 30-75% of the cars arrested several times because of drunk driving get back in the car.
This would be prevented by Alcolock, as the system connected to the vehicle determines the level of alcohol in the air which is blown out of the air. If it is greater than permitted, or if the driver has not blown into the device at all, the system will not allow the vehicle to start.
The cost of the instrument of more than EUR 1000 would be borne by the infringer.
A study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such instruments could reduce the number of infringements by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people's lives could be saved every year by this rule.
The measure focuses on violations for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from turning into crimes,
On the other hand, it is easier to introduce it, as the implementation of the legal reform is carried out in the usual context, while the necessary reform of criminal matters would require an amendment to the basic law.
The instrument is not available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in experimental mode.
Tomorrow, the House of Representatives will vote on the initiative of the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party, which calls for the integration of the system into school buses, as a French model.
