Those who speak in their sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up and tell them what happened to them that day, but those who talk when they sleep.
The phenomenon may seem scary at first, but it's actually completely harmless.
This is called benign sleep disorder somniloquism.
It's quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure more people have been told he spoke at night.
In terms of its frequency, it can be completely rapsodic (for example, only once in patients with a high fever) or more regular (once a day, once a week or once a month), and usually the next day the child will not remember anything.
His appearance cannot be traced back to a single trigger.
It is often associated with other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night alarm, night bed urination (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is not legal.
As we have already mentioned, it can be a condition with high fever, or a phenomenon of stress or excitement.
In any case, it has been studied less so far.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It may be quiet, calm, it may be incoherent with words, murmur, but unlike all this, it may also appear in the form of shouting, crying, or a longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is advisable to observe the child and contact a specialist. The study may reveal whether there is a problem of great anxiety and thus offer a solution.
As we have already mentioned, it is a benign phenomenon and therefore there is no cure unless it is associated with another manageable form of sleep disorder (e.g. insomnia or stress situation).
However, there are some things we can do, and here are a bunch of preventive measures:
Make sure the child stays calm before going to bed.
Choose soothing games and avoid the child watching scary or more aggressive TV shows or shows.
