Blood's safe again.
The Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday. President Dr. Francine Décary had a good reason to celebrate because Hema-Québec has now become one of the safest and most effective blood donors in the world.
Most importantly, he managed to regain the trust of people, which was severely swayed by the scandal in the 1980 and 1990's infected blood.
As is known, the national blood reserve treated by the blood supply service to the Canadian Red Cross was infected with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and the general uproar, the government of Canada, led by Judge Horace Krever, launched an official investigation in February 1994, which was designed to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make proposals to avoid future similar cases.
While Judge Krever's delay in submitting his report, some provinces set up their own committee to plan a new blood treatment system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee completed this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood supply services were established in Canada: one is the Québeet server Hema-Québec, and the other is the Canadian blood supply company responsible for all other provinces and the two Territories.
"When the Hema-Québec began its activities in 1998, only 38% of the people had confidence in Québec's blood supply system," said Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
"In the coming years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in this area, we have managed to regain people's trust." Décary proudly states that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the people in Quebec believed Hema-Québec to be reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that 'trust is extremely fragile'.
Since the creation of Hema-Québec on 28 September 1998, it has applied the precautionary principle.
During this period, many cases of mad cow disease, the new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, have been discovered in Europe, the doctor, who has been controlling the company since its foundation in 1998.
"We had no idea if this disease was spreading through blood.
Therefore, we have been relying on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever- and Gélineau reports. Thus, if we are unsure about this and there is a risk of serious illness, we must apply exclusion measures. In this case, Creutzfeldt-Jakob is the disease that causes brain changes and inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999 we did not accept blood from persons who have spent more than one month in the UK since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was unquestionably found that the disease was spreading through blood.
"This case has convinced us that it makes sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999, there was a technique on the market that allows for a much more sensitive diagnosis of HIV virus. This is the nucleic acid test (NAT), which can directly detect the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, rather than the antibodies to the virus that have been used before.
With the NAT test, we could shorten the window period, which lasts as long as the virus can be detected in the blood using our technical means, explains the expert.
This period could be reduced for a period of less than one week.
Thus, there was a significant reduction in the risk of blood transmitters infecting the blood stock unknowingly and that this could not be detected.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of the spread of AIDS through blood transfusion.
Nowadays, the risk of someone getting HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
"In other words, that means we should distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with the HIV virus.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400 and 500 thousand blood products each year, more than 24 years should pass to allow such a case to occur and someone to be infected with HIV by a blood product.
I think that anyone can now accept or prescribe blood transfusions in order to restore health, says the number one head of the Hema-Québec.
"The challenge of the next decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogen gets into the system.
After all, it was only last year that the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, gets into the blood with insect bites.
We must therefore be constantly on our guard, 'continued Dr. Décary, and then stressed that apart from emergency reserves, Hema-Québec must provide sufficient permanent reserves.
"The ageing of the population increases the demands.
Since anti-cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need to replace red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the stock of blood taxes, as the number of people in the network who are capable of giving blood represents only 3% of the population in Quebec.
However, every healthy person, at least 18 years of age, fulfilling the eligibility criteria can give blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average 14% of applicants do not accept blood because they are infected with AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have been in a country where malaria destroys are not eligible for blood donation for a year.
"With these three percent, we have enough to meet the needs of hospitals.
It's very rare that we run out of supplies.
However, we need to increase the number of blood taxes to the extent that the existing ones age, because they can't give blood after a while.
But it's very difficult to convince people to give blood, but it's even harder to keep them and get them to become regular blood donors.
In this rushing world today, a man has less than an hour to go out and give blood, "says Francine Décary.
Hema-Québec, which is an annual budget of $297 million, provides not only blood products but also human tissues, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin tissue, which are used almost exclusively for severely burned persons.
These tissues are analysed, modified and frozen and placed at Hema-Québec, which also manages a single public stem cell bank in Québec.
Once only the umbilical cord treated as medical waste can be obtained from blood that is rich in stem cells and allows for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated entering our bank for the millennium umbilical blood sample, and we plan to remove over a thousand new samples a year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering them for organ transplants, "said Dr. Décary, who said that the cord blood removal program is very popular these days.
"Many mothers are sad because they do not have the opportunity to do so" - it is true, because Hema-Québec is not able to make this complex and costly program available at all Québec hospitals.
