Opinion - The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
On September 17, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Deputy CEO of the Barrick Gold mine in Canada.
According to Orwelli, Garver claims that the world's largest gold-producing company has filed a six-million-dollar libel suit against three authors and a small-money publishing company to initiate a so-called "public debate."
Although judges are independent and impartial, their decision, especially in libel suits, is made not on the basis of the truth, but on the basis of the law.
It's no surprise that Garver kept quiet about this fundamental difference.
Is it really the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate is to destroy anyone whose position is contrary to his?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publishers of the Noir Canada book must spend significant amounts on defence and struggle in an unequal fight where on the other side is an army of lawyers supported by almost inexhaustible resources in the mining industry.
In such an unequal fight, they often use the tactic of destroying the defendant and making friendly agreements, which not only silence the contrary, but also intimidate those who would try to deal with the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, he should have expressed his views in public.
Although in many other countries where Barrick Gold is active, this is done differently, in Canada, the disputing parties usually do not hit each other with sticks, but tell their thoughts.
The mine would therefore have had to open its books and files and prepare for a real debate in the press, media and publications, paying independent research groups that could shed light on the issue.
But it seems that Barrick Gold does not trust public opinion, and in one move, it is pushing aside the requests and letters written to protect the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can initiate a 'public' debate if, at the same time, he disregards the opinion of this public?
In the vice-president's mind, this is probably just a word for a well-paid lawyer, not for the entire population of Canada: the meaning of the concept is narrowing down a lot.
In a democratic state, even those who abuse others deserve freedom of speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are mainly supported by the public because it condemns the harsh process of the mine.
The public is prepared to listen to Barrick and to make a judgment, but it would do so on the basis of civilised arguments, rather than by an action for silence for many. (In the context of the term 'public debate', Barrick Gold recently called in writing to the authors of Noir Canada to refrain from using this term.)
