Wall Street rescue mission - Democrats and Republicans agreed
Yesterday, the Republicans and Democratic leaders of the Bush Government and Congress finally reached an agreement on an economic rescue mission, which has been the biggest plan since the great economic crisis in the 1930s.
The 700 billion US dollar plan to stop the financial crisis that has been raging on Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by the two houses of Congress.
Essential points of the plan: more effective control of implementation by Members; new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the State funds envisaged; new provisions to keep the number of houses seized due to non-payment; right of access to the salaries of the managers of the companies receiving assistance.
American finance minister Henry Paulson, Nancy Pelosi, president of the American House of Representatives, and Judd Gregg, the Republican representative in the trial, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, after the two-day marathon trial was over.
"We have made great progress towards a solution that will work effectively on the markets," said Henry Paulson, representative of the Bush Government.
"We have done everything to save the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis on Wall Street," said the Democrat.
"The most important aspect is that if we don't do this, then there will be a huge shock, chaos and confusion in the everyday lives of Americans," said Republicans Judd Gregg.
The trial was accelerated in the last few hours, in fear that another failure would have an adverse effect on the mood of investors.
The agreement was granted until the stock market opened this morning.
The two presidential candidates, who joined the negotiations late, have shown willingness to agree, but they have nevertheless expressed their lack of satisfaction at the fact that the situation has escalated to the end.
Senator Barack Obama has attributed to himself the extension of the agreement with elements such as provisions relating to the preservation of house property or the payment of the heads of companies assisted by the State.
"When we ask taxpayers to take certain extraordinary steps to ensure that other people are irresponsible, it is not very welcome.
"But these steps are necessary," he said on a television show in America.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another network to vote in favour of the proposed plan, he replied, "I would like to know the details, but I hope so."
"What I have read in broad terms is that it is something that we all need to digest and that we can move forward with.
The opportunity to do nothing is simply unacceptable, "he said.
According to the 700 billion-dollar plan, taxpayers' money would be used to buy the dubious demands of American financial institutions, something at risk, unsalvageable assets.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis, which led to the collapse of risky real estate loans (secondary mortgage loans) and then spread to other debt (commercial) securities and, finally, the freezing of liquid resources and the deregulation of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft agreement was overthrown by a group of Republicans last week.
It seems that we have managed to get out of this dead end since the Democrats agreed to provide certain "toxic" tools for firms in difficulty rather than buying them up.
In order to ensure that all members of Congress are satisfied, a provision has been included in the plan, which provides that if the government has to bear losses within the framework of the programme for five years, it may impose new taxes to recover its resources.
As part of the new plan, a tranche of $250 billion would first be paid; this could be followed by an additional 100 billion if the President considered it necessary.
The payment of the remaining $350 billion should be approved by Congress by another vote.
In return for assistance, Washington will acquire a share in the subsidised companies, which will give it dividends and which it can sell after the crisis has been brought down.
The Federal Government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure of property to cover the mortgage loans covered by the plan, and may also set a maximum rate of pay and severance payments for the managers of companies affected by the crisis.
The designers of the plan would like the plan to be voted on today by the House of Representatives and by the Senate on Wednesday.
