Psychology of overbidding: why are we giving out more money?
In the auctions, buyers tend to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurologic-economic basis of this known - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been revealed by neurologists and economists at the University of New York.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to be left behind in a race such as the auction of eBay, so they also pay too high a price.
Research was trying to map this "game" nervous system scheme through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group participated in an auction, while the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method was used to test the active brain areas of the experimental persons.
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but during the auction game, in which an overbidding of the other party is essential, the complex under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, was activated intensively when the game was lost.
This brain area plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system in addition to several other functions.
Therefore, according to researchers, price uplifting can be explained by avoiding the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theory, the members of the research group of economists also conducted a financial follow-up investigation.
In this three groups bid against a partner under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the realistic value of the product concerned and they made their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they were won out of the game, they would get another $15 in reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 just before the auction, but in the event of a losing auction, the members of the group also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups was, therefore, only that one of them was stressed about winning or losing.
However, in evidence of the hypothesis of neurologists, members of the "against loss" team were willing to bet higher than the control group and the winning group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
To date, they have only explained the events at the auction with the joy of victory and risk avoidance.
Only the neurological imaging methods helped to resolve the discrepancy between these two theories with a third explanation now, "said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
There are about half a billion people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and among the leading causes of death in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned.
There are hundreds of thousands of people with hepatitis here, but they only treat seven thousand, which is why patients often don't know they're infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infections caused by various viruses.
Their symptoms have many similarities, characterized by inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are different.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the gastrointestinal tract (e.g. contaminated food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretions, saliva).
Travellers should definitely be vaccinated against virus A and B, and there is no vaccine against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two to three weeks after exposure to the infected food, with general malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints, nausea.
After this, jaundice on the skin and white eyes occurs, faeces becomes clear, urine becomes dark, healing can take two to three weeks.
One million people worldwide die of a more severe type of disease, liver cancer caused by hepatitis B and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only every tenth infected receive medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated, it can lead to liver shrinkage and liver cancer.
Most of the infected people don't even know about their disease because the pathogen is subversely destroying liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms occur in 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening tests are very important.
In three groups, there are far more than average cases: people who had had transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
There are currently 200 million people in the world infected with chronic hepatitis C virus.
As the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is recommended to seek medical advice when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
When the disease can be cured in time, the virus can be eradicated from the body so that the infection ceases and the cancer can be prevented.
30 September is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was first held in 2004 by the organisations representing patients around the world.
It aims to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
