The trance of the trance is imitated by the intelligent car
What would be the best way to develop technologies to avoid collision if not to imitate obstacle sensors in the world of nature?
Bees, for example.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebee bees gave Nissan's engineers the strategic idea of how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built the BR23C Biotope Control System, a robotic minivan, which was provided with the characteristics of the bees, with the ultimate aim of helping to develop a system that eliminates all collisions.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is in fact very similar to our safety barrier, explained at the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, technological PR and research and development brand director.
An important role is the complex eye of the uterus, which can see in every direction at a angle of more than 300 degrees.
In order to copy the function of the composite eye, engineers touched the idea of a laser telemetry.
This will identify obstacles, calculate their distance and send a signal to the on-board microprocessor in a 180-degree field of vision before the BR23C, which will immediately transform into an operation to avoid impact.
Within a fraction of a second, the barrier is detected, and then the auto-box, mimicking the movements of the uterus, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid impact.
In any way other than the current system, this evasive maneuver is conducted in a fully intuitive manner.
"If this were not so, the car robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the Mobility Laboratory and the driver of the auto-robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety barrier, a layer within which impact is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bee does in order to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in an instant.
However, in a way other than bees, the discrepancy must not be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, only two-dimensional and only in the direction of wheel inversion.
Thus, instead of the infinite possibility available to bees to avoid other bees, only rotation and acceleration and deceleration have been used as an option available for the auto-box.
BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer life span than lithium-ion.
Andoh says that a instinctive intelligent response is important, not the ability to process data, even less store them.
This device must process and respond to only a few input signals per second.
There is no need to preserve them and respond to intuitive logic based on the data of previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There's no need for gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step in the development of instant bypass technology that Nissan estimates can enter serial-made cars within 10 years.
An additional application may be possible to combine the unit with the GPS-satellite navigation system in order to lead the car to the specified end-destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
