The written version of the $700 billion economic rescue package law for the purchase of banks' bad loans has been completed.
They spend half the amount in the first round.
At the time of the east coast, during the further talks until after midnight on Saturday, Congress leaders reached a conclusion in the debate around a total of $700 billion rescue package for days, said Reuters.
"We have made serious progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic President of the American House of Representatives, who said that only the agreement had to be put on paper.
The compromise on the package was supported by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Minister of Finance Henry Paulson has stated that the programme will work and will be effective, but there must be more to be done. According to Pelosi, this is not about saving Wall Street, but about reversing the economic wagon.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets in Washington on Sunday evening at 8: 00 p.m. (i.e. Monday morning at 2: 00 p.m. Central European time), but did not cause a spectacular uppercut in the prison.
The draft legislation on the programme, which is entitled the 2008 Economic Emergency Stabilization Act, will be voted on by the House of Representatives first on Monday and then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and the White House also welcomed the news of the settlement.
We are pleased with the progress made last night and we appreciate the efforts of the two parties to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy, said Tony Fratto, spokesman for the White House.
Moreover, the programme differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which would have meant that the $700 billion would have been spent on the purchase of bad-quality, credit-backed securities.
In the first round, up to half of the sum of 700 billion can be spent immediately after Congress is expected to vote on the matter on Monday, of which the Ministry of Finance buys bad-credit securities, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the decision of the President.
The programme will be monitored by a separate body, which will include the President of the Federal Reserve.
The spending of the other half of 700 billion depends on another decision by Congress.
Under the law, the Ministry of Finance can use a combined tactic: it can purchase bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities at the same time and other types of "toxic" loans.
The purchase may take place in auctions and directly - it has been notified by the Ministry's authorities.
The legislation allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme where the financial wallet guarantees assets of concern for which the companies will pay a fee corresponding to the expected damage.
Henry Paulson said that the law provides the necessary means of obtaining up to $700 billion for the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the widespread purchase of bad assets, whether it is their insurance or the avoidance of systemic risk associated with the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
However, the bosses of banks in distress and waiting for state help can expect the government to limit their withdrawal money, which the overseas slang simply calls a gold parachute.
Payments are limited only in certain cases, and the limits depend on how the Ministry of Finance helps.
In essence, the restriction means that if the Ministry buys at auction, an additional tax will be levied on the gold parachute, unless they retire the reduced bank leader.
When purchasing bad loans directly, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that management money is not excessive.
The picture includes the fact that existing gold parachute contracts are not changed, the restriction applies only to new ones, so as to encourage participation in the programme.
This is the first time in American history that there will be legal restrictions on the remuneration of CEOs, commented on the measure by the President of the Committee on Financial Services of the House of Representatives, Barney Frank, the Democratic Party.
In addition, in the banks involved in the scheme, the State obtains the right to acquire a share and thus the risk of taxpayers is reduced, since they can ultimately win the transaction as soon as the economy and the bank that has been saved recover.
The bill states that for the next five years, the President will have to submit to Congress a proposal providing for the return of the expected losses to taxpayers from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed their doubts about the plan.
"This is not what the American citizens have asked us to do, which means that it does not protect the taxpayers' dollars," said the Republican Congressman Darrell Issa, California.
His Democratic colleague, Mary Kaptur, of Ohio, believed that the measures were encouraged by the same people who were responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
