The figures show the seriousness of a phenomenon that is still one of the most common causes of death today and requires almost twice as much sacrifice as murder.
Today, for the 58th time, Anmil is hosting the day of the victims of accidents at work, traditionally held on the second Sunday of October, in all the counties of Italy, to draw the attention of the institutions, social organisations and mass communication to this dramatic problem.
"The worrying data provided by Anmil and the tragic events of recent days show that prevention in accidents at work has an extremely important role," said the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano, in his message to Pietro Mercandelli, the President of the National Association of Accident at Work.
The head of state sincerely commended the 'association's persistent commitment to prevention at work, to the protection of the interests of workers in accidents, to help victims' families and to making public opinion '.
"Natural and honestly divided outrage is caused by these kinds of tragedies, which, by their size, also attract the interest of the media and the public, but in reality, we have to face dramatic, repeated and repeated cases every day."
Napolitano openly admits: 'There is no doubt a shortage of resources, funding education and information is crucial.
Intra-school initiatives aimed at direct education of young people on the verge of entering the world of work are of paramount importance.
It is our duty to maintain interest in this phenomenon, not to ignore the social importance of this issue, and we need more effective legislation to enforce it.
The President of the Lower House, Gianfranco Fini, stressed for his part, "how serious accidents at work end in death are of social importance to all of us, and they require the institutions to put an end to this as soon as possible."
"Data on accidents at work show a slight improvement, but the number of deaths of this type is still extremely high," said Pietro Mercandelli, President of the Anmil.
"At the same time, we do not want this downward trend to be combined with decreasing attention, because the biggest tragedies are happening when attention falls."
"We believe that, at a general level, we are still not doing everything we can to combat this phenomenon, which could be resolved through a complex action programme.
In our opinion, more stringent supervision and control would be needed, said Mercandelli, and a stronger intervention in the field of labour training, starting from school education. '
"Further efforts are needed to inform and secure public opinion," he added.
What is most needed, however, is a more responsible employer environment in relation to a phenomenon that is a problem at social level. '
Then Mercandelli criticised "the gradual deterioration of the protection net for victims of accidents at work 'and" aid policy towards which the system has been drifting in recent years'.
"The aim is therefore to give the workers back the security provided by the insurance, because the fate of those who suffer from the accident cannot depend on the arbitrary measures of legislators, and on their distribution."
Hearing damage can be caused by MP3 players
May cause permanent hearing damage by listening to portable player devices for longer periods of time and high volume, such as MP3 devices -
in its report published in Brussels, the European Commission, on the basis of the opinion published today by the EU Scientific Committee on New and Newly Identified Health Risks (SCENIHR).
"The opinion shows that 5-10 percent of people who listen to their portable music player for more than one hour per day for five years can suffer hearing damage."
"It is worrying that young people who use portable music players and mobile phones that operate on a high volume of sound often are not aware of their irreversible potential to damage their hearing," said Meglena Kuneva.
"Scientific surveys indicate an undisputed risk, which we urgently need to respond to," said the Commissioner.
The most important task is to inform consumers and disseminate information about them widely.
In the light of that opinion, we also need to review existing control systems so that they can operate effectively and keep up with the latest technologies. '
Brussels asked the independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem in view of the prevalence of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise damage.
The European Commission, in cooperation with the Member States and stakeholders, is ready to examine the possible measures that could be taken to protect children and minors exposed to noise caused by portable players and similar devices, "said the member of the committee.
The current European safety standard sets out 100 dB maximum noise levels for portable music players, but there is an increasing concern about hearing damage caused by excessive use of such sound sources.
At the same time, there are solutions such as reducing the level and duration of noise pollution by which these hearing damage can be significantly reduced.
In the opinion of the EU Scientific Committee, it explains that when using a portable player device with a high volume of music (more than 89 decibels) for five hours a week, noise pollution exceeds the current maximum noise level at work.
If you listen to music for a longer period of time in similar circumstances, there is a risk of permanent hearing damage after five years.
This affects about 5-10% of the users of portable equipment, which could mean 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
