In danger of the elite
The phenomenon was felt a few days ago when the House of Representatives did not vote in favour of the 700 billion dollar rescue package presented by the White House: much of the Americans were more interested and still interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is also supported by yesterday's New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis has caused a break in the Republican Party, which shows an ever-increasing division between the traditional, moderate, Eastern-Coast attitude to support federal institutions and business circles and the ever-increasing new anti-Washington and Financial World line in the Central and South States.
This line was expressed in a critical way during the vote in the House referred to in the introduction.
However, this event is only one of the major changes that economic restructuring still taking place indicates or allows us to see, and not only in the United States, but also in the entire Western world, and perhaps beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the US and in Europe, will only speed up the long-standing phenomena that have been solidifying in this new climate and will finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-updating, the renationalisation of the dual category of state sovereignty into public consciousness, a sort of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis concerns banking and financial institutions which, although they have close links with the rest of the world, are, first and foremost, and quite widely, bringing with them people and families that live in a single country, in a single state.
This is, however, a direct political difficulty for those in the government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people who are also electorate.
Therefore, the crisis appears to be global in economic terms, but it is almost exclusively national in political terms.
It appears that political internationalism is essentially off the coast: the European Union, which, lagging between different interests and different national strategies, is not able to set a single political line.
Thus, everyone expects the intervention, the rescue package, the recovery and the new rules, but most of all, the opening up of funds: because, in times of crisis, only individual states have economic resources, financial resources that can make things right.
They also have the means and the authority to use them: under certain circumstances they have two invaluable resources that no other market and no international organisation will ever have in this way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed by the crisis on national statehood is fully in line with the fact that the economic growth that has taken place recently attaches to an increasing importance that is closely linked to this element: this is territorial.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of increasingly sophisticated technology, and we were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we suddenly had to realise that our future depended more and more on things such as water, crop and oil.
Things that can be transported from one side of the planet to another, but they can be completely linked to a demarcated place, an area.
So whoever controls the area has a lot more cards than one who, unfortunately, was born in a place where there is no crop, no oil and no water.
I would also like to turn to the second novelty, which suggests a sort of fault line.
Anyone who says "territory, state, government," necessarily says "politics," in other words, "driving."
From this point of view, the economic crisis seems to produce two conflicting phenomena:
On the one hand, an objective recognition of the need for credible leadership, someone who can handle the events.
On the other hand, the current leadership, especially economic leaders, has resulted in a total loss of faith, who have proved to be completely inadequate and have proved that many of them still have a vague area ahead of them.
Together, the two are even deeper and more disturbing in a sense: the loss of faith, impatience, incompetence and isolation, which affects the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
So it seems that there is a growing belief in the wider population that the time of the social elite at its peak has expired. It expired before their actions, experiences, ways of life, culture, in the complex sense of the word, they became self-absorbed, thus making the social elite increasingly alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In other words, the need for leadership, in its veiled form, provides a broad but strong delegation movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This manifests itself in the unexpected "revolts" of voters, or in the recent sudden changes in the public mood. Such as the conservatives' access to power in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the Labour Party unit in Great Britain, or the rebellion of US congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the Italian right).
It seems that the traditional elite, along with their parties, programmes, and even their customs, press and notable intellect, seem to understand less and less and less and less what has been happening for some time in the deeper layers of Western society. Furthermore, the economic crisis is growing, spreading and potentially capable of creating more and less passion.
In spite of all this, talking about the impending rebellion of the masses would, frankly, be excessive.
But it doesn't hurt to keep your eyes open.
