Good-bye, old Cinema Paradiso, the days of the old cinema in the cities are over.
Traditional cinemas are closing in for the multiplexes.
"A city with no movies, a blind city, like a face without eyes."
The pictures taken by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively illustrate everything that takes place in Italian cities, but also in rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the appearance of large multi-chamber cinema in the suburbs and, as a result, the depopulation of single-grown people in city centres - is an inevitable and irreversible process, but at the same time bears all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
When historical and memorable places disappear, "it's like a friend of ours going away, a friend of ours who shared our journey and many experiences with us," says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which was the Oscar Award 20 years ago and the Cannes Festival Grand Prize for Tornatore, tells the lyrical story of a small-town cinema after a movie that might have been lost forever.
The largest association of operators, Anec, is clear: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinema theatres have closed. The biggest losses were recorded by cinema in large cities: 10 cinemas in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin, and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna, which lost 82 single-chamber cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardia (41).
And that, for their disappearance, the multiplexing of multiplexes is not more likely to prove it than the number of newly opened multi-room cinemas in these three regions of Italy, which have increased by 195 in the last five years in Lombardia, 81 in Tuscany and the same in Emilia-Romagna.
"The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally," says the President of Anec Paolo Protti. "It is okay to build new facilities, but it is also necessary to ensure the survival of the existing ones, because when an urban cinema closes, not all visitors are willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention unfilled financial funds intended to support operators: the state's outstanding debt is about EUR 10 million.
From both ethical and moral point of view, it is shameful that the government does not comply with the legislation in force.
In order to maintain the market, EUR 16-18 million per year would be needed. '
This is the first Italian city, which, in its concern for closures, decided to remedy the problem by means of an agreement between the municipality and Anec to protect and boost small-town cinema in the suburbs and downtown.
The provisions would include tax advantages to operators and benefits to the public to facilitate accessibility: viewers can drive to restricted zones and park at preferential tariffs in certain parking spaces.
"I like this initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities, even by introducing other measures, will follow the example of Bologna.
However, it is also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to fight the rule of multiplexes, need to improve sound and image quality, because today's audience is much more demanding.
Protecting the traditional cinema was always an important issue for me: closing the Superperinema in Bagheria - where I spent my childhood and youth - gave me the spark that made me finally do Cinema Paradiso, even though I've been thinking about it for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, so when I go to the closed Rialto or Quirinale to see no blackened posters, I turn my head. I've had so many experiences here. "
