Serious charges have been made against the Mayor and Vice-Mayor of Gioia Tauro, Giorgio Dal Torrione and Rosario Schiavone, and the Mayor of Rosarno, Carlo Martelli, who were arrested this morning for external involvement in a criminal conspiracy.
Handcuffs were placed on the hands of a lawyer nephew named Giovachino Piromalli, a senior middleman between the clan and the administration, who had previously been convicted of participating in a mob-like crime syndicate and had been compensated for EUR 10 million.
"The disregard of all legal and moral rules, more than good taste, is written by state prosecutors." The two local authorities have declared their intention to pay an advisory fee to counsel Piromalli.
"So the clan would have had official access to city hall, which would have given us an additional opportunity to control and control public administration, which is already significant.
The President of the General Assembly of the Calabria region, Agazio Loiero, does not hide that "there are many collusions between the local institutions and the organised underworld": there are areas where the proliferation of the mafia is stronger than elsewhere, where collusion is almost inevitable.
However, many local politicians resist the pressure of 'ndrangheta, they are the heroes who remain clean'.
This morning's arrests are the continuation of July events, when the police announced that they had managed to decapitate the Pyromalli clan.
At the end of April, local politicians were relieved of their mandate to manage the municipality. Gioia Tauro's municipal committee was disbanded once in 1991 because of the alleged conflicts between organised crime and the local government.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, Christian Democrat mayor who was in charge of the right-centre coalition in the second round of 2006.
He cried a scandal when the County House ordered the dissolution of the municipal committee.
He brought the former Deputy Minister of the Interior to trial Marco Mindini and accused him of planning everything for political purposes, but the court stated in the arrest warrant signed this morning that the Pyromalli clan had gone to the point of demanding that the A3 project be changed.
From the eavesdropping of Dal Torrione, the state prosecutors say, "he was willing to meet the demands of an extensive contractor representing a group known to be close to the Pyromalli family, and to subordinate the decisions of the municipality to the Clan interest."
The energy comes from the waves, and now comes the big ones.
An inexhaustible energy source that accounts for 70% of the planet's surface, and which is only now being discovered by large international energy companies.
Waves, sea currents, tides, all renewable energy sources, to which giants like Chevron, who are now trying to put their hands on it.
They have been searching for hundreds of years for the possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea. In the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research has increased.
Around 1980, when the price of oil decreased, the idea of using marine energy was put aside, but today the need for environmental protection and the rise in oil prices give the industry new impetus.
The London World Energy Council (WEC) estimates in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity demand could be covered by installations using sea wave.
This amount is twice what nuclear power plants are currently producing.
Besides, there would still be currents and tides.
The Titans are in motion.
Enersis was the first company to commit to maritime energy and signed an agreement on a power plant in Northern Portugal in 2005.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signature was announced.
Two years have passed, and more and more companies have voted in favour of marine energy, including those who have been committed to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying the technologies that exploit the energy of the oceans and considering the possibility of cooperating with us," said the spokesperson of an associated company of the American oil giant, Wall Street Journal, to the economic newspaper.
The cooperation in question concerns the acquisition of a licence to launch a project for the exploitation of marine energy in Alaska issued by the US Energy Commission.
The matter is of no small importance, especially considering the fact that the US is currently in Alaska producing oil, and even President Bush has recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. and Ocean Power in New Jersey are on the road to energy that can be extracted from the sea.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
According to experts, it is still primitive technology, even because energy from the sea does not dispel doubts about environmental impact.
The existing facilities such as those of Portugal or Scotland are all small and therefore do not cause too much problems in terms of the ecosystem.
However, in order to produce energy on a larger scale, installations which have a significant environmental impact are needed.
There are several possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a connected buoy system.
The shocks generated by the waves and moving buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressures by the pistons and cylinders in them.
The pressure is turning a turbine that feeds a generator.
The electric current goes to land on cables under the sea.
For the time being, there are four similar facilities at the planning stage, which are now waiting for a federal permit, and some of the energy produced would be used in a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started producing energy for a shopping mall and a parking lot with six underwater turbines in the East River Strait of New York.
At tides, the movement of water turns the turbine blades, and this whirlwind nourishes the generator.
Verdant stated that it has a long list of partners who are only waiting for the permits to use energy.
Waves after tides.
At present, particular attention should be paid to the potential to be exploited by tidal tides.
Although it is a temporary phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, so they can be considered as a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as the other coastal states spent $7.5 million in 2008 to exploit the energy supplied by the tides, which is projected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
